# Importing the cards data from all rows

path = './data_treated_no_probs/'
X_train = pd.read_parquet(path + 'X_train.parquet')
y_train = pd.read_parquet(path + 'y_train.parquet')
X_test = pd.read_parquet(path + 'X_test.parquet')
y_test = pd.read_parquet(path + 'y_test.parquet')

# Defining the function used to plot the ROC AUC curve
def roc_auc_curve(y_pred_prob, title, threshold = 0.5):
    # Convert probabilities predictions to binary (0 or 1) based on a threshold
    y_pred_class = (y_pred_prob > threshold).astype(int)
 
    # Calculate ROC curve
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_prob)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
 
    # Plot ROC curve
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, label='ROC curve (area = {:.2f})'.format(roc_auc))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()

# Identify categorical columns
categorical_cols = ['type', 'user_gender', 'creator_gender', 'impressTime_wday',
                    'user_province_grouped', 'contentId_grouped', 'talkId_grouped']

# Identify numerical columns
numerical_cols = [col for col in X_train.columns if col not in categorical_cols]
# Removing the id columns
numerical_cols.remove('mlogId')
numerical_cols.remove('userId')

# Create a column transformer numerical scaling
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', StandardScaler(), numerical_cols)
    ],
    remainder='passthrough'
)

# Droping the card and user id for the training
X_train.drop(['mlogId', 'userId'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# Fitting the data
X_train_std = preprocessor.fit_transform(X_train)

# Store the user card group in another df
user_card_group = X_test[['mlogId', 'userId']]

# Droping the card and user id for the training
X_test.drop(['mlogId', 'userId'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# Get feature names after one-hot encoding
feature_names = preprocessor.get_feature_names_out()

In order to get a first glimpse of the data and the training process, we train a simple tree with maximum depth of 3. We also use the plot from this tree to inspect the top features.

In [4]:
# Set the max depth for the tree
max_depth = 3

tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=0, max_depth = max_depth, criterion='entropy', class_weight='balanced')

# Fit decision tree on the training data
tree.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get feature importances
feature_importances = tree.feature_importances_

# Create a dictionary to associate feature names with importances
feature_importance_dict = dict(zip(feature_names, feature_importances))

# Round feature importances to 3 decimal places
rounded_importances = {feature: round(importance, 3) for feature, importance in feature_importance_dict.items()}

# Get features with importance greater than 0
positive_importances = {feature: importance for feature, importance in rounded_importances.items() if importance > 0}

# Sort positive importances
sorted_positive_importances = sorted(positive_importances.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=False)

# Plot the positive feature importances
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.barh(range(len(sorted_positive_importances)), [importance for _, importance in sorted_positive_importances], align='center')
plt.yticks(range(len(sorted_positive_importances)), [feature for feature, _ in sorted_positive_importances])
plt.xlabel('Feature Importance')
plt.title('Features with Importance > 0')
plt.show()

# Calculate the y_scores
y_pred_prob = tree.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Calculate ROC curve
roc_auc_curve(y_pred_prob, f"ROC curve for max depth = {max_depth}")

# Print the accuracy of the simple tree
print(f"The accuracy of the model is {accuracy_score(y_test, tree.predict(X_test))}")

The accuracy of the model is 0.445018

The simple tree model is able to give a ROC that is above the threshhold of .5. The ROC value is not far from the fully tuned logistic regression model, but the accuracy is quite low still, which is expected for such a simplistic model.

The next step is to use cross validation to test different hyper-parameter combinations. For that, we select trees with increasing maximum depths, changing criterion and minimum sample splits. The best paramaters are then used in the main modelling notebook.
